		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2017"></a><br><code>sle2017/paper09</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2017</a> paper:</span><br><i>Concrete syntax: a multi-paradigm modelling approach</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/YentlVanTendeloo.html">Yentl Van Tendeloo</a>, <a href="../profile/SimonVanMierlo.html">Simon Van Mierlo</a>, <a href="../profile/BartMeyers.html">Bart Meyers</a>, <a href="../profile/HansVangheluwe.html">Hans Vangheluwe</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3136014.3136017">10.1145/3136014.3136017</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1a.html"><span class="tagM">T1A: Design</span></a><ul><li> It proposes a multi-paradigm approach to defining concrete syntax, i.e., language design of notations.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The work is motivated by domain-specific modeling languages and how their syntax is defined.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4f.html"><span class="tagL">T4F: Visualisation</span></a><ul><li> Concrete syntax work typically spans visual/textual notations, and the paper explicitly targets multi-paradigm (incl. visual) syntax.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> It emphasizes coordinating multiple syntactic paradigms for the same language, requiring integration between notation forms.
</li></ul></li></ul>
